  <p><strong>Chimney fires are one of the most common causes of house fires in Australia — and one of the most preventable.</strong> Many happen without the homeowner realising. By the time there's visible damage, the fire has already done its worst inside the flue.</p>

  <p>Here's what causes them, how to spot the signs, what to do if one starts, and the one thing that prevents almost all of them.</p>

  <h2>What Causes a Chimney Fire?</h2>

  <p>Almost every chimney fire has the same root cause: <strong>creosote buildup.</strong></p>

  <p>Creosote is a dark, tar-like substance that forms when wood smoke cools inside the flue. Every fire deposits a thin layer on the flue walls. Over time — especially when burning wet wood or running the heater on a low smoulder — those layers build up. And creosote is highly flammable.</p>

  <p><strong>When a hot fire is lit in a flue with heavy buildup, the deposits ignite.</strong> A chimney fire burns at temperatures exceeding 1,100°C — hot enough to crack flue liners, warp metal pipes, ignite roof timbers, and cause serious structural damage.</p>

