  <h2>How to Prevent a Chimney Fire</h2>

  <p>The good news: chimney fires are almost entirely preventable. There are three things that together eliminate virtually all risk.</p>

  <p><strong>Get the flue professionally cleaned every year.</strong> This is the most important one. A professional clean removes the creosote deposits before they accumulate to a dangerous level. For most Melbourne households using a wood heater through winter, once a year is sufficient. If you're burning 5+ nights a week through the whole season, twice a year is worth considering.</p>

  <p><strong>Burn dry, seasoned hardwood only.</strong> Wet wood produces far more smoke at lower temperatures — the exact conditions that cause rapid creosote buildup. Source wood that has been dried for at least 12 months. In Melbourne, red gum, ironbark and box are the best options. Avoid pine, treated timber, or anything that hasn't been properly seasoned.</p>

  <p><strong>Don't run the heater on a constant low smoulder.</strong> A fire that's starved of oxygen to extend the overnight burn creates thick, cool smoke that coats the flue rapidly. If you want overnight heat, build a larger fire on full air for 30–40 minutes before closing the vents down — rather than running it low all evening. And don't close the vents all the way.</p>

  <h2>What About Insurance?</h2>

  <p>Most home and contents insurance policies cover chimney fire damage — but many have conditions attached. A common exclusion is failure to maintain the chimney or flue to a reasonable standard. If a chimney fire occurs and the insurer determines the flue hadn't been cleaned or maintained, a claim can be reduced or rejected entirely.</p>

  <p>An annual professional clean, with a receipt, is reasonable evidence of maintenance. It's a $249 receipt that could matter significantly if a claim ever needs to be made.</p>

  <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>Chimney fires are common, dangerous, often silent — and almost entirely preventable with one annual professional clean. The cost of a flue clean is a fraction of the cost of repairing chimney fire damage, and an even smaller fraction of what a structural house fire costs in damage, displacement and insurance complications.</p>

  <p>If your flue hasn't been cleaned in the last 12 months, book it before you light the first fire of the season. It takes about an hour and removes the risk completely.</p>

